Anyway, I walk around the house, and I try not to look at things, try not to think of her. But that's all I can do. All I do is feel this deep pain, this deep longing. I see her again. I remember when I was in Germany, and she left.

That she feels good, feels no pain, is happy. If there isn't, I'll probably never see her again. Unless there's some other side, like hell. How she may get to that side, I don't know how that would be. She was too much of a saint.

That... I couldn't believe my luck. I was so excited to be with her. Or going to be with her again when I lived in Chandler and she lived in Spokane. We connected again through email. And we started talking and texting and emailing. I was so excited.

I dreamt the other day when I would see her again and be with her. At least see her again. I finally got to in 2007. It took us two weeks to decide we loved each other still... looking at the old emails. Or less than two weeks, I don't know.

She didn't go out with anybody. She died. It's really hard to accept sometimes. I feel lonely. I feel lost. I feel like I don't have anybody there for me anymore... who can pick up the slack, when I'm lacking. I guess that I'm glad she's not in pain. I sure miss her.

And I walk around the house and sometimes I think just momentarily that she'll be back to take care of this or that. And I realize she'll never be back. She didn't go away on a trip. She didn't go away on vacation, she's not at work. She didn't go to the store.
